<div class="dcf-wrapper">
<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>CrowdStrike (CRWD)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of CrowdStrike Holdings, Inc. — using latest financial actuals, disclosed assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated 2024-03-24</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  {roundedIV === null ? (
    <div class="verdict-card" style="margin-top: 60px; padding: 40px; text-align: center;">
      <h2 style="margin: 0; border: none; font-size: 1.5rem;">Data Unavailable</h2>
      <p>We could not fetch the required financial data from StockAnalysis.com to run the DCF model. Please try again later.</p>
    </div>
  ) : (
    <>
      <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
      <div class="verdict-card">
        <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
        <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
        <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice !== null ? currentPrice.toFixed(2) : 'N/A'} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
        <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
          {verdictText}
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
      <div class="stats-row">
        <div class="stat-card">
          <div class="stat-value">{currentRevenue !== null ? `$${(currentRevenue / 1000).toFixed(2)}B` : 'N/A'}</div>
          <div class="stat-label">Current Revenue</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-card">
          <div class="stat-value">{baseFCF !== null ? `$${(baseFCF / 1000).toFixed(2)}B` : 'N/A'}</div>
          <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-card">
          <div class="stat-value">{currentEPS !== null ? `$${currentEPS.toFixed(2)}` : 'N/A'}</div>
          <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-card">
          <div class="stat-value">{opMargin !== null ? `${opMargin.toFixed(1)}%` : 'N/A'}</div>
          <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-card">
          <div class="stat-value">{netCash !== null ? `$${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(2)}B` : 'N/A'}</div>
          <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
      <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
      <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

      <div class="method-step">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
          <p>CrowdStrike generated <strong>${baseFCF !== null ? (baseFCF / 1000).toFixed(2) : 'N/A'} billion</strong> in free cash flow in the most recent period. As a SaaS company, FCF is much higher than Net Income due to massive upfront billings (deferred revenue) and stock-based compensation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-step">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
          <p>We grow FCF at <strong>{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% per year</strong> for 5 years. This assumes CrowdStrike maintains rapid growth driven by its Falcon platform expanding into identity, cloud security, and Next-Gen SIEM, while gaining immense operational leverage.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-step">
        <div class="step-num">3</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
          <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}% forever</strong>. Cybersecurity is fundamentally a defensive moat, and enterprise switching costs for endpoint security are notoriously high. The Gordon Growth Model calculates the value of all cash flows from Year 6 to infinity.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-step">
        <div class="step-num">4</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
          <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}%</strong> — our required rate of return. With the 10Y Treasury at {treasuryRate}%, a {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% hurdle rate appropriately models the equity risk premium for a high-growth, high-multiple technology company.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="method-step">
        <div class="step-num">5</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
          <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (${netCash !== null ? (netCash / 1000).toFixed(2) : 'N/A'}B) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding ({sharesOutstanding !== null ? sharesOutstanding : 'N/A'}M) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
      <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
      <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math.</p>

      <div class="assumption-grid">
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
          <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}%</div>
          <div class="rationale">
            CrowdStrike's revenue growth has historically exceeded 30%, but at a $3B+ run-rate, the law of large numbers applies. A 22% FCF CAGR over 5 years is highly ambitious but achievable for an apex predator in cybersecurity, as gross margins are high and scaling software requires minimal incremental capital.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
          <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}%</div>
          <div class="rationale">
            10Y Treasury: {treasuryRate}%. Using CAPM with a tech beta, the cost of equity sits around 9-11%. We use 10%. We demand a 10% annual return to justify owning a stock trading at rich multiples, protecting against multiple contraction.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
          <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
          <div class="rationale">
            Cybersecurity budgets are non-discretionary and likely to grow structurally faster than global GDP (typically 2-3%). A 4% terminal rate implies CrowdStrike remains deeply entrenched in global enterprise infrastructure essentially forever.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
      <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
              <th>FCF ($M)</th>
              <th>PV Factor</th>
              <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Base ({latestYearLabel})</td>
              <td>{baseFCF !== null ? `$${baseFCF.toLocaleString()}` : 'N/A'}</td>
              <td>—</td>
              <td>—</td>
            </tr>
            {projectedFCF.map(p => (
              <tr>
                <td>Year {p.year}</td>
                <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
                <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
                <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
            <tr class="row-total">
              <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
              <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
      <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
              <th>Value ($M)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Year 6 FCF (Year 5 × 1.04)</td>
              <td>${Math.round(projectedFCF[4].fcf * (1 + growthRateTerminal)).toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Terminal Value (FCF₆ ÷ (10% − 4%))</td>
              <td>${terminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="row-total">
              <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
              <td class="highlight-cell">${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ FINAL CALCULATION ═══ -->
      <h3>Final Valuation</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
              <th>Value ($M)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>PV of Phase 1 Cash Flows</td>
              <td>${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
              <td>${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>= Enterprise Value</td>
              <td>${enterpriseValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>+ Net Cash (Cash − Debt)</td>
              <td>{netCash !== null ? `$${netCash.toLocaleString()}` : 'N/A'}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>= Equity Value</td>
              <td>${equityValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>÷ Shares Outstanding</td>
              <td>{sharesOutstanding !== null ? sharesOutstanding.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="row-total">
              <td>Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
              <td class="highlight-cell">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ HISTORICAL CHARTS ═══ -->
      <h2>Financial Track Record</h2>
      <p>Before trusting a forward projection, look at where the company has been.</p>

      <h3>Revenue ($M)</h3>
      <div class="bar-chart">
        {revenueHistory.map(r => (
          <div class="bar-row">
            <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
            <div class="bar-track">
              {r.value !== null ? (
                <div class="bar-fill revenue" style={`width: ${(r.value / maxRev) * 100}%`}>
                  ${r.value.toLocaleString()}
                </div>
              ) : (
                <span style="color: #5a6a80; padding-left: 12px;">N/A</span>
              )}
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <h3>Free Cash Flow ($M)</h3>
      <div class="bar-chart">
        {fcfHistory.map(r => (
          <div class="bar-row">
            <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
            <div class="bar-track">
              {r.value !== null ? (
                <div class={`bar-fill fcf ${r.value < 0 ? 'negative' : ''}`} style={`width: ${Math.abs(r.value / maxFCF) * 100}%`}>
                  {r.value < 0 ? `-$${Math.abs(r.value).toLocaleString()}` : `$${r.value.toLocaleString()}`}
                </div>
              ) : (
                <span style="color: #5a6a80; padding-left: 12px;">N/A</span>
              )}
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <h3>Earnings Per Share (Diluted)</h3>
      <div class="bar-chart">
        {epsHistory.map(r => (
          <div class="bar-row">
            <div class="bar-label">{r.year}</div>
            <div class="bar-track">
              {r.value !== null ? (
                <div class={`bar-fill eps ${r.value < 0 ? 'negative' : ''}`} style={`width: ${(Math.abs(r.value) / maxEPS) * 100}%`}>
                  ${r.value.toFixed(2)}
                </div>
              ) : (
                <span style="color: #5a6a80; padding-left: 12px;">N/A</span>
              )}
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ MARGIN TRENDS ═══ -->
      <h3>Margin Trends</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
              <th>Operating Margin</th>
              <th>Profit Margin</th>
              <th>FCF Margin</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {marginHistory.map(m => (
              <tr>
                <td>{m.year}</td>
                <td>{m.operating !== 'N/A' ? `${m.operating}%` : 'N/A'}</td>
                <td>{m.profit !== 'N/A' ? `${m.profit}%` : 'N/A'}</td>
                <td>{m.fcfMargin !== 'N/A' ? `${m.fcfMargin}%` : 'N/A'}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p><strong>Key observation:</strong> SaaS models exhibit high FCF margins early because cash is collected upfront (Deferred Revenue), while GAAP operating/profit margins lag heavily due to expensing massive R&D and Stock-Based Compensation over time.</p>

      <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
      <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
      <p>Our base case uses {(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(0)}% growth and {(discountRate * 100).toFixed(0)}% discount rate. How does the intrinsic value change if we tweak these assumptions?</p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table class="sensitivity-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
              {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
                <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
              ))}
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
              <tr>
                <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
                {row.values.map((v, i) => (
                  <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                    ${v}
                  </td>
                ))}
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
      <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
      <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses.</p>

      <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Module Adoption:</strong> Customers buying more Falcon modules per core deployment creates immense operating leverage that could push FCF margins higher than historical peaks.</li>
        <li><strong>Vendor Consolidation:</strong> A broad macro trend of enterprises abandoning dozens of point solutions in favor of unified platforms like CrowdStrike.</li>
        <li><strong>AI LogScale:</strong> Success in their SIEM and observability product lines could drastically accelerate revenue beyond the core endpoint market.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Execution / Outage Risk:</strong> As evidenced by past major software update incidents, reputational damage in cybersecurity is costly and can lead to immediate churn and litigation.</li>
        <li><strong>Stock-Based Compensation:</strong> Much of the FCF is driven by non-cash SBC. True FCF (adjusted for SBC) is lower. Dilution eats into the per-share value over time.</li>
        <li><strong>Competition:</strong> Microsoft is bundling security heavily, and Palo Alto Networks is aggressive in the platform space, which may eventually compress pricing power.</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Why is CrowdStrike's FCF so much higher than Net Income?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">Two main reasons: 1) Deferred Revenue. Customers pay for 1-3 year subscriptions upfront in cash, but the revenue is recognized monthly over time (Net income). Cash flow immediately captures the upfront billings. 2) Stock-Based Compensation. They pay employees heavily in stock options, which is an expense on the income statement (lowering Net Income) but added back on the cash flow statement since it's a non-cash expense.</div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Is SBC dilution captured here?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">Partially. The model divides total equity value by the <em>current</em> fully diluted shares outstanding. However, it does not forecast future dilution. In reality, sustained high SBC requires the company to eventually use free cash flow to buy back shares simply to offset dilution, effectively reducing cash available to shareholders.</div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Why use a 10% discount rate?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">While the 10-year Treasury is {treasuryRate}%, high-growth tech stocks require a higher hurdle rate to justify the risk of buying far-future cash flows. 10% is a standard institutional baseline for large-cap software, protecting against multiple compression in a rising rate environment.</div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </>
